Sure, here's an example of a basic model for an App user in C#:

```
public class AppUser
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Username { get; set; }
    public string Password { get; set; }
    public string Email { get; set; }
    public bool IsAdmin { get; set; }
    public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; }
    public DateTime LastLogin { get; set; }
}
```

This model includes properties for the user's ID, username, password, email, admin status, and timestamps for when the user's account was created and last logged in. Of course, the properties in your own App user model may differ depending on the requirements of your specific application.

Sure, here's an updated version of the `AppUser` model that uses `Guid` for the `Id` property and instantiates it with a random `Guid` value:

```
public class AppUser
{
    public Guid Id { get; set; } = Guid.NewGuid();
    public string Username { get; set; }
    public string Password { get; set; }
    public string Email { get; set; }
    public bool IsAdmin { get; set; }
    public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; }
    public DateTime LastLogin { get; set; }
}
```

With this updated version, the `Id` property is initialized with a new random `Guid` value when a new instance of the `AppUser` class is created. This ensures that each user in your application will have a unique identifier.
